k that computation, that is, ratiocination, has place only in numbers, as if man were distinguished from other living creatures (which is said to have been the opinion of <i id="mwAvQ"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pythagoras" title="Pythagoras" id="mwAvU">Pythagoras</a></i>) by nothing but the faculty of numbering; for <i id="mwAvY">magnitude, body, motion, time, degrees of quality, action, conception, proportion, speech and names</i> (in which all the kinds of philosophy consist) are capable of addition and substraction <span typeof="mw:Transclusion mw:Entity" about="#mwt53" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sic","href":"./Template:Sic"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAvc"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt53" id="mwAvg">[</span><i about="#mwt53" id="mwAvk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sic" title="Sic" id="mwAvo">sic</a></i><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt53" id="mwAvs">]</span>. Now such things as we add or substract, that is, which we put into an account, we are said to <i id="mwAvw">consider</i>, in Greek λογίζεσθαι [<i id="mwAv0">logizesthai</i>], in which language also συλλογίζεσθι [<i id="mwAv4">syllogizesthai</i>] signifies to <i id="mwAv8">compute</i>, <i id="mwAwA">reason</i>, or <i id="mwAwE">reckon</i>."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-19" id="cite_note-19"><a href="./Reason#cite_ref-19" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-19" class="mw-reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFHobbes" class="citation" about="#mwt54" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"citation","href":"./Template:Citation"},"params":{"first":{"wt":"Thomas"},"last":{"wt":"Hobbes"},"title":{"wt":"The English Works of Thomas Hobbes"},"volume":{"wt":"3 (Leviathan)"},"chapter":{"wt":"VII. Of the ends, or resolutions of discourse"},"chapter-url":{"wt":"http://oll.libertyfund.org/?option=com_staticxt&amp;staticfile=show.php%3Ftitle=585&amp;chapter=89830&amp;layout=html&am