 Press. 2012. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwA9c">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwA9g"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-19-966107-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-19-966107-7" id="mwA9k">978-0-19-966107-7</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Natural+Signs+and+Knowledge+of+God%3A+A+New+Look+at+Theistic+Arguments&amp;rft.place=Oxford&amp;rft.edition=Reprint&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2012&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-966107-7&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReason" class="Z3988" about="#mwt260" id="mwA9o"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt260" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwA9s"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-76" id="cite_note-76"><a href="./Reason#cite_ref-76" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-76" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt265" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"http://www.stephenjaygould.org/library/gould_noma.html"},"title":{"wt":"Nonoverlapping Magisteria"},"author":{"wt":"Stephen Ja Gould"},"date":{"wt":"1997"},"website":{"wt":"www.stephenjaygould.org"},"access-date":{"wt":"2016-04-06"},"quote":{"wt":"\"To say it for all my colleagues and for the umpteenth millionth time (from college bull sessions to learned treatises): science simply cannot (by its legitimate methods) adjudicate the issue of God&apos;s possible superintendence of nature. We neither affirm nor deny it; we simply can&apos;t comment on it as scientists.\""}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA9w">Stephen Ja Gould (1997). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.stephenjaygould.org/library/gould_noma.html" id="mwA90">"Nonoverlapping Magisteria"</a>. <i id="mwA94">www.stephenjaygould.org</i><span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwA98">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwA-A">2016-04-06</span></span>. <q id="mwA-E">To say it for all my colleagues and for the umpteenth millionth time (from college bull sessions to learned treatises): science simply cannot (by its legitimate methods) adjudicate the issue of God's possible superintendence of nature. We neither affirm nor deny it; we simply can't comment on it as scientists.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=www.stephenjaygould.org&amp;rft.atitle=Nonoverlapping+Magisteria&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.au=Stephen+Ja+Gould&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stephenjaygould.org%2Flibrary%2Fgould_noma.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReason" class="Z3988" about="#mwt265" id="mwA-I"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt265" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwA-M"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-77" id="cite_note-77"><a href="./Reason#cite_ref-77" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-77" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt266" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite book","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"title":{"wt":"The God Delusion"},"last":{"wt":"Dawkins"},"first":{"wt":"Richard"},"year":{"wt":"2008"},"publisher":{"wt":"Mariner Books"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-618-91824-9"},"edition":{"wt":"Reprint"},"language":{"wt":"English"},"chapter":{"wt":"4"},"quote":{"wt":"This sounds terrific, right up until you give it a moment&apos;s thought. You then realize that the presence of a creative deity in the universe is clearly a scientific hypothesis. Indeed, it is hard to imagine a more momentous hypothesis in all of science. A universe with a god would be a completely different kind of universe from one without, and it would be a scientific difference. God could clinch the matter in his favour at any moment by staging a spectacular demonstration of his powers, one that would satisfy the exacting standards of science. Even the infamous Templeton Foundation recognized that God is a scientific hypothesis — by funding double-blind trials to test whether remote prayer would speed the recovery of heart patients. It didn&apos;t, of course, although a control group who knew they had been prayed for tended to get worse (how about a class action suit against the Templeton Foundation?) Despite such well-financed efforts, no evidence for God&apos;s existence has yet appeared."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA-Q">Dawkins, Richard (2008). "4". <i id="mwA-U">The God Delusion</i> (Reprint ed.). Mariner Books. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwA-Y">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwA-c"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-618-91824-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-618-91824-9" id="mwA-g">978-0-618-91824-9</a>. <q id="mwA-k">This sounds terrific, right up until you give it a moment's thought. You then realize that the presence of a creative deity in the universe is clearly a scientific hypothesis. Indeed, it is hard to imagine a more momentous hypothesis in all of science. A universe with a god would be a completely different kind of universe from one without, and it would be a scientific difference. God could clinch the matter in his favour at any moment by staging a spectacular demonstration of his powers, one that would satisfy the exacting standards of science. Even the infamous Templeton Foundation recognized that God is a scientific hypothesis — by funding double-blind trials to test whether remote prayer would speed the recovery of heart patients. It didn't, of course, although a control group who knew they had been prayed for tended to get worse (how about a class action suit against the Templeton Foundation?) Despite such well-financed efforts, no evidence for God's existence has yet appeared.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=4&amp;rft.btitle=The+God+Delusion&amp;rft.edition=Reprint&amp;rft.pub=Mariner+Books&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-618-91824-9&amp;rft.aulast=Dawkins&amp;rft.aufirst=Richard&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReason" class="Z3988" about="#mwt266" id="mwA-o"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt266" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwA-s"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-78" id="cite_note-78"><a href="./Reason#cite_ref-78" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-78" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt267" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://www.amazon.com/Consciousness-Existence-God-Routledge-Philosophy-ebook/dp/B001QA4T5A/ref=sr_1_fkmr0_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1459966694&amp;sr=8-1-fkmr0&amp;keywords=theistic+argument+from+consciousness"},"title":{"wt":"Consciousness and the Existence of God: A Theistic Argument"},"last":{"wt":"Moreland"},"first":{"wt":"J.P."},"publisher":{"wt":"Routledge"},"access-date":{"wt":"2016-04-06"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA-w">Moreland, J.P. <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" hr